autolisp-test-recap-crash-got-t — run-all report/recap stages raise "got T"
===========================================================================

Reported from: running the autolisp-test conformance harness against
clautolisp 1.2.13 (SBCL), Linux, while verifying the rtos/distance
float-format fix (system-variables.issue).

Status: open — characterised, root cause NOT yet isolated.

Summary
-------

A full `(autolisp-test-run-all)` runs all test files and per-test
results correctly (the 3915 tests execute and the per-entry results
list is well-formed), but the three post-run aggregation stages crash:

    [autolisp-test] matrix raised: FOREACH list argument must
                    evaluate to a proper list, got T.
    [autolisp-test] write-sexp-report raised: FOREACH list argument
                    must evaluate to a proper list, got T.
    [autolisp-test] print-recap raised: LENGTH expects a proper list,
                    got T.

Each stage is wrapped in autolisp-test--guarded, so the run does not
abort — the report.sexp is still written — but the matrix is empty and
no human-readable recap is printed. The verdict summary is therefore
lost for any run that hits this.

Repro
-----

    $ clautolisp --no-init -x '(progn (load "autolisp-test/harness/run.lsp")
                                      (autolisp-test-run-all))' -q
    ;; ... 3915 tests run ...
    ;; [autolisp-test] no expectations file at:
    ;;     autolisp-test/harness/expectations/BRICSCAD/1.2.13/unknown.lsp
    ;; [autolisp-test] matrix raised: FOREACH ... got T.
    ;; [autolisp-test] write-sexp-report raised: FOREACH ... got T.
    ;; [autolisp-test] print-recap raised: LENGTH ... got T.

(run from the repository root so the harness' "autolisp-test/" path
prefix resolves.)

What was ruled out
------------------

The "got T" is a value reaching FOREACH / LENGTH that is the symbol T
rather than a list. Investigation so far did NOT find it in the obvious
places:

- The detected DESCRIPTOR is well-formed:
    ((IMPL . BRICSCAD) (IMPL-NAME . BricsCAD) (VERSION . 1.2.13)
     (PLATFORMS) (RUNTIMES EXPRESS-TOOLS USER-INPUT GRAPHICS DCL
     OBJECTDBX ARX VLR VLAX-CURVE COM VLAX) (PROFILE-TARGET . BRICSCAD))
- RESULTS from autolisp-test-run-many is a proper list of 3915 alists;
  no result entry is a non-list / T.
- No test ENTRY has a non-list meta, nor a profile / platform-tags /
  runtime-tags / tags slot equal to T.
- The missing expectations overlay is handled correctly:
  autolisp-test-load-expectations returns nil, and
  autolisp-test-apply-expectations with a nil overlay returns RESULTS
  unchanged (same length).
- Calling autolisp-test-matrix DIRECTLY on the exact (entries,
  descriptor, results) triple — including after the load/apply-
  expectations round-trip — does NOT raise. The crash only manifests
  inside autolisp-test-run-all.
- The autolisp-test--guarded mechanism itself is not at fault in the
  obvious way: a list-built (lambda nil ...) applied via
  vl-catch-all-apply within a defun DOES see that defun's /-locals as
  free variables (verified with a standalone probe), so the guarded
  thunks' references to entries/descriptor/results/matrix should
  resolve to run-all's locals.

Leads (not yet confirmed)
-------------------------

Because the crash reproduces ONLY through run-all and NOT when its
steps are replayed by hand on the same data, the trigger is most
likely stateful: something accumulated while the 3915 tests run, read
back by the aggregation stages. The guarded thunks reference
`entries`, `descriptor`, `results`, `matrix` as FREE variables; the
prime suspect is a deftest body somewhere in the corpus doing an
unqualified `(setq <name> ...)` that leaks a global which shadows /
collides with one of those names (or with a report-stage local such as
total / pass / fail) and is bound to T. Worth doing:

- Bisect the corpus: run-all over progressively smaller manifests
  until the crash disappears, to find the polluting test file.
- Audit deftest bodies for unqualified setq of: results, entries,
  descriptor, matrix, total, pass, fail, skip, n, acc, r, entry, tag.
- Have autolisp-test--guarded capture and log the offending value
  (type + identity) so the next failure names the variable.

Why it matters
--------------

- Every clautolisp version bump produces a NEW
  expectations/<IMPL>/<VERSION>/<host>.lsp path that does not exist
  yet, so the "no expectations file" branch is the common case — and
  this crash rides along with it on essentially every dev run.
- The verdict matrix and recap are the harness' primary human-readable
  output; losing them silently (the run still "succeeds" and writes a
  report) is a poor failure mode.

Related
-------

- Surfaced during system-variables.issue (rtos/distance float-format
  verification, clautolisp 1.2.13).
